      • OPT_OUT_IDFA

        public static final java.lang.String OPT_OUT_IDFA
        Value provided to identifyUser(String, String[]) to opt out of collecting an IDFA for this specific user.
        If you prevent Teak from collecting the Identifier For Advertisers (IDFA), Teak will no longer be able to add this user to Facebook Ad Audiences.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • OPT_OUT_FACEBOOK

        public static final java.lang.String OPT_OUT_FACEBOOK
        Value provided to identifyUser(String, String[]) to opt out of collecting a Facebook Access Token for this specific user.
        If you prevent Teak from collecting the Facebook Access Token, Teak will no longer be able to correlate this user across multiple devices.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • OPT_OUT_PUSH_KEY

        public static final java.lang.String OPT_OUT_PUSH_KEY
        Value provided to identifyUser(String, String[]) to opt out of collecting a Push Key for this specific user.
        If you prevent Teak from collecting the Push Key, Teak will no longer be able to send Local Notifications or Push Notifications for this user.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • LAUNCHED_FROM_NOTIFICATION_INTENT

        public static final java.lang.String LAUNCHED_FROM_NOTIFICATION_INTENT
        Intent action used by Teak to notify you that the app was launched from a notification.
        You can listen for this using a BroadcastReceiver and the LocalBroadcastManager. 
         
     IntentFilter filter = new IntentFilter();
     filter.addAction(Teak.LAUNCHED_FROM_NOTIFICATION_INTENT);
     LocalBroadcastManager.getInstance(context).registerReceiver(yourBroadcastListener, filter);
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • identifyUser

        public static void identifyUser(java.lang.String userIdentifier,
                                java.lang.String[] optOut)
        Tell Teak how it should identify the current user, with data collection opt-out.

        This should be the same way you identify the user in your backend.

        Parameters:
        userIdentifier - An identifier which is unique for the current user.
        optOut - A list containing zero or more of: OPT_OUT_IDFA, OPT_OUT_FACEBOOK, OPT_OUT_PUSH_KEY

      • identifyUser

                                java.lang.String[] optOut,
                                java.lang.String email)

        This should be the same way you identify the user in your backend.

        Parameters:
        userIdentifier - An identifier which is unique for the current user.
        optOut - A list containing zero or more of: OPT_OUT_IDFA, OPT_OUT_FACEBOOK, OPT_OUT_PUSH_KEY
        email - The email address for the user.

                                  long count)
        Increment the value an arbitrary event in Teak.
        Parameters:
        actionId - The identifier for the action, e.g. 'complete'.
        objectTypeId - The type of object that is being posted, e.g. 'quest'.
        objectInstanceId - The specific instance of the object, e.g. 'gather-quest-1'
        count - The amount by which to increment.

      • getNotificationStatus

        public static int getNotificationStatus()
        Has the user disabled notifications for this app. This will always return 'false' for any device below API 19.
        Returns:
        'true' if the device is above API 19 and the user has disabled notifications, 'false' otherwise.

      • openSettingsAppToThisAppsSettings

        public static boolean openSettingsAppToThisAppsSettings()
        Open the settings app to the settings for this app. Be sure to prompt the user to re-enable notifications for your app before calling this function. This will always return 'false' for any device below API 19.
        Returns:
        'true' if Teak was (probably) able to open the settings, 'false' if Teak was (probably) not able to open the settings.

      • setApplicationBadgeNumber

        public static boolean setApplicationBadgeNumber(int count)
        Set the badge number on the icon of the application. Set the count to 0 to remove the badge.
        Returns:
        'true' if Teak was able to set the badge number, 'false' otherwise.
